        "id": "unit_1774782178531",
        "title": "Unit 4:  SPREADSHEET BASICS",
        "order": 4,
        "notes": "<p><strong>&nbsp;MS Excel - Practical</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>&nbsp;A. How to Use Excel</strong></p><p></p><p>- Microsoft Excel is a powerful spreadsheet program used for organizing and analyzing data.</p><p>- It consists of worksheets, which are made up of cells organized in rows and columns.</p><p>- Excel offers a wide range of features and functions to perform calculations, create charts, and manipulate data.</p><p></p><p><strong>&nbsp;B. Starting Excel</strong></p><p></p><p>- To start Excel, click on the Windows Start menu, search for Excel, and click on the Excel application to launch it.</p><p></p><p><strong>&nbsp;C. Parts of Worksheet</strong></p><p></p><p>- The Excel worksheet consists of rows and columns forming cells.</p><p>- The intersection of a row and a column is called a cell.</p><p>- Cells can contain data such as text, numbers, or formulas.</p><p></p><p><strong>&nbsp;D. Navigating in a Worksheet</strong></p><p></p><p>- Use the arrow keys or the mouse to navigate between cells.</p><p>- Pressing the Tab key moves the active cell to the right, and Shift + Tab moves it to the left.</p><p>- Pressing Enter moves the active cell down, and Shift + Enter moves it up.</p><p></p><p><strong>&nbsp;E. Getting to Know Mouse Pointer Shapes</strong></p><p></p><p>- The mouse pointer in Excel changes based on the current action.</p><p>- The regular mouse pointer is used for selecting cells or navigating.</p><p>- When hovering over the border of a cell, the pointer changes to a crosshair, allowing you to adjust cell size.</p><p>- When hovering over the fill handle, the pointer changes to a solid cross, enabling you to autofill cells.</p><p></p><p><strong><u>&nbsp;CREATING SPREADSHEET</u></strong></p><p></p><p>A. Starting a New Worksheet:</p><p>- Open Excel and click on \"Blank Workbook\" to start a new worksheet.</p><p></p><p>B. Entering the Three Different Types of Data in a Worksheet:</p><p>- Text: Type text directly into the desired cell.</p><p>- Numbers: Type numbers directly into the desired cell.</p><p>- Formulas: Begin a formula with the equals sign (=) followed by the desired calculation.</p><p></p><p>C. Creating Simple Formulas:</p><p>- Select the cell where you want the result to appear.</p><p>- Type the formula using cell references and appropriate operators, e.g., \"=A1+B1\".</p><p></p><p>D. Formatting Data for Decimal Points:</p><p>- Select the cell or cells you want to format.</p><p>- Click on the \"Home\" tab.</p><p>- Use the Number Format dropdown to select the desired decimal format.</p><p></p><p>E. Editing Data in a Worksheet:</p><p>- Double-click on the cell you want to edit.</p><p>- Make the necessary changes to the cell content.</p><p></p><p>F. Using AutoFill:</p><p>- Enter a value or series of values in a cell.</p><p>- Position the cursor on the bottom-right corner of the cell until it turns into a fill handle.</p><p>- Click and drag to autofill adjacent cells with the desired pattern.</p><p></p><p>G. Blocking Data:</p><p>- Select the range of cells you want to block.</p><p>- Right-click on the selection and choose \"Format Cells\" to access formatting options.</p><p></p><p>H. Saving a Worksheet:</p><p>- Click on the \"File\" tab.</p><p>- Choose \"Save As\" to specify a name and location for the worksheet.</p><p>- Select the desired file format and click \"Save\" to save the worksheet.</p><p></p><p>I. Exiting Excel:</p><p>- Click on the \"File\" tab.</p><p>- Choose \"Exit\" or click the Close button (X) to exit Excel.</p><p></p>"
